PISA 2012 Data Exploration¶

by John Platter¶

Investigation Overview¶

I have gleaned a number of insights related to the interactions of student achievement in math, wealth distribution, weekly math education minutes, and a number of other variables. I hope to provide you with the same a-ha moments I had through the use of clear visuals that communicate these findings free from distractions.

Dataset Overview¶

The PISA 2012 is a massive standardized test of Reading, Science and Math given to 15 year old students across 66 different countries. The data also includes a thorough survey of more than 400 attributes. I focused on a few that interested me and came to surprising conclusions as well as conclusions that resonated with my own personal understanding of the world.

Distribution of Wealth Across the PISA dataset¶

The world has a great variety of income levels. Generally, wealth has a left skew, meaning there are a lot more people who have less than people who have a lot. Also, observe the multi-modal spikeyness of the distribution showing clusters of countries who have similar amounts of wealth. Note 0 is the global measure of center and the ticks show deviations left and right of 0.

Categorical Correlations with Wealth¶

Notice how most of the variables leave the wealth distribution unchanged, but GRADE shows clear positive interaction with wealth. GRADE is the student's grade compared to where the average 15 year old is in their country.

Wealth, Achievement, and Grade¶

This plot demonstrates how Wealth, Achievement and Grade vary, first on one plot, then faceted by grade. Notice how low grades occupy the bottom left of the graph, demonstrating lower achievement and lower wealth.

USA vs Finland Math Achievement, by Category¶

This final plot examines how Students in the US and Finland did on their math test grouped by how they answered their survey questions. I love noticing the small differences between the red and blue lines, as these each tell interesting stories about students in the perspective countries
